ce:section.ce:para:
This home-made Si-CDs column is tested under RPLC, HILIC and IEC conditions on a conventional HPLC instrument. The chromatograms of tested compounds are shown in Fig. 3
                        , Fig. S2 and Fig. S3, respectively. The chromatographic parameters including retention factor (k), column efficiency (N), asymmetry factor (As
                        ) and resolution (Rs
                        ) are listed in Table 1
                        . Dead time is determined by solvent peak. Under RPLC mode, alkylbenzenes, polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs), alkaloids, pesticides, antibiotics and glycosides all achieve good separation with an average N of 10000 plates/m. For four adjacent analytes of triadimefon, tebuconazole, diniconazole and diclofop, the resolution reaches 3.77, 2.34 and 5.17 within 15 min. Under HILIC mode, nucleosides and bases obtain satisfactory separation with an average N of 15000 plates/m. The resolution of adenosine, xanthosine, cytidine and guanosine achieve 3.11, 2.75 and 5.38 within 10 min. Under IEC mode, charged compounds including inorganic anions, organic acids and amphoteric sulfonamides are selected as test objects to measure the ion exchange performance of the Si-CDs column. The average N achieves 14000 plates/m under IEC mode, the resolution of 3,4-dimethoxybenzoic acid, benzoic acid, 4-chlorobenzoic acid and 1-naphthoic acid is 2.09, 7.15 and 2.63 within 10 min. Experimental results show that this Si-CDs column is suitable for three chromatographic separation modes with good column efficiency.
